{{note|Notea|n.b.1}}The family name "Mrnjav<U+010D>evi<U+0107>" was not mentioned in contemporary sources, nor was any other surname associated with this family. The oldest known source mentioning the name "Mrnjav<U+010D>evi<U+0107>" is ''Ruvar<U+010D>ev rodoslov'' "The Genealogy of Ruvarac", written between 1563 and 1584. It is unknown whether it was introduced into the Genealogy from some older source, or from the folk poetry and tradition.<ref>Rudi<U+0107> 2001, p.96.</ref><br/>
{{note|Noteb|n.b.2}}This liturgical book, acquired in the 19th century by Russian collector [[Aleksey Khludov]], is kept today in the [[State Historical Museum]] of Russia.<br/>
{{note|Notec|n.b.3}}The name Despotovi<U+0107> ("[[Despot (court title)|despot]]'s son") was applied in a similar way to Uglje<U+0161>a, the son of Despot [[Jovan Uglje<U+0161>a]], King Vuka<U+0161>in's younger brother.<ref name=rudic/><br/>
